            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this Rhode Island income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates your Rhode Island state income tax using a
                progressive bracket system. You enter your income and basic
                adjustments, and the calculator:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Combines wages, self‑employment, and other taxable income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtracts pre‑tax deductions (like 401(k) and HSA
                  contributions).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Applies a simplified Rhode Island standard deduction
                  assumption.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtracts any Rhode Island‑specific income adjustments you
                  enter.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Calculates tax in each Rhode Island bracket and subtracts RI
                  tax credits.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The result is an estimate of your
                <strong>Rhode Island taxable income</strong>,
                <strong>state tax due</strong>, and
                <strong>effective tax rate</strong> (state tax divided by total
                income).
              </p>

              <h3>Rhode Island income tax formula (simplified)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>1. Total income</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Total income} = \text{Wages} + \text{Self‑employment}
                  + \text{Other income} \)
                </p>

                <p class="mt-3"><strong>2. Adjusted income</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Adjusted income} = \text{Total income} -
                  \text{Pre‑tax deductions} \)
                </p>

                <p class="mt-3">
                  <strong>3. Rhode Island taxable income (approx.)</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{RI taxable income} = \max\big(0,\; \text{Adjusted
                  income} - \text{Standard deduction} - \text{RI
                  adjustments}\big) \)
                </p>

                <p class="mt-3"><strong>4. Rhode Island tax</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Tax is computed by applying each marginal rate to the portion
                  of income in that bracket, then subtracting credits:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{RI tax} = \sum (\text{Taxable amount in bracket}_i
                  \times \text{Rate}_i) - \text{RI credits} \)
                </p>

                <p class="mt-3"><strong>5. Effective tax rate</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Effective RI rate} = \dfrac{\text{RI
                  tax}}{\text{Total income}} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
                Note: Actual Rhode Island returns use federal AGI, Rhode Island
                modifications, exemptions, and credits defined in state law.
                This calculator uses reasonable defaults for planning, not
                filing.
              </p>

              <h2>Rhode Island income tax brackets</h2>
              <p>
                Rhode Island uses a <strong>three‑bracket</strong> progressive
                income tax system. The same brackets apply to most filing
                statuses, but your deductions and credits can differ.
              </p>
              <p>
                The calculator is pre‑loaded with current Rhode Island rates and
                thresholds. As your income rises, only the portion of income in
                each higher bracket is taxed at the higher rate.
              </p>

              <h3>Example: middle‑income Rhode Island taxpayer</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose you are single with $75,000 in wages and no other income
                or adjustments:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Total income: $75,000</li>
                <li>Pre‑tax deductions: $0</li>
                <li>
                  Approximate RI taxable income after standard deduction: about
                  $X (varies by year)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Part of that income is taxed at 3.75%, part at 4.75%, and the
                  rest at 5.99%.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator shows how much of your income falls into each
                bracket and the tax generated in that bracket.
              </p>

              <h2>Rhode Island vs. federal income tax</h2>
              <p>
                When you enable the
                <strong>federal comparison</strong> checkbox, the tool also
                estimates your federal income tax using:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Current federal tax brackets for your filing status.</li>
                <li>A standard deduction assumption (no itemizing).</li>
                <li>No special federal credits or additional taxes.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>This gives you a quick view of:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Your <strong>federal taxable income</strong> and federal tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your <strong>combined effective rate</strong> (federal + Rhode
                  Island).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your <strong>take‑home pay after both income taxes</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <p>
                To keep the calculator fast and easy to use, it makes several
                simplifying assumptions:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Uses a single standard deduction model rather than every Rhode
                  Island exemption rule.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not separately model capital gains, qualified dividends,
                  or alternative minimum tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not calculate every Rhode Island credit (you can enter a
                  total credit amount manually).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not include payroll taxes (Social Security and Medicare),
                  local taxes, or health insurance premiums.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For complex situations—such as multi‑state income, large capital
                gains, business losses, or detailed credit eligibility—use
                professional tax software or consult a tax professional.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Rhode Island income tax</h2>

              <h3>Do I have to file a Rhode Island income tax return?</h3>
              <p>
                In general, you must file a Rhode Island return if you are a
                resident, part‑year resident, or non‑resident with Rhode
                Island‑source income and your income exceeds the state’s filing
